LEPROSY - SOLOMON ISLANDS: (HONIARA) INTERNALLY DISPLACED PERSONS CENTERS
*************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 11 Jun 2014
Source: Radio New Zealand/International [edited]
http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/246925/24-cases-of-leprosy-confirmed-in-solomon-islands


Save the Children in Solomon Islands says there's an outbreak of leprosy affecting 24 people living in displaced people's centres in Honiara.

The head of logistics and emergency, Graeme Kenna, says no one has died from leprosy but the situation is stretching the health services in Solomon Islands as the country struggles to recover from the severe flooding in April [2014]. 27 evacuation centres were set up after the April floods in which thousands were left homeless and at least 22 people died.

"Leprosy does happen in Pacific Island countries. But to have a sudden reporting of 24 cases, most of them in young children, is quite alarming. The government is telling us and the World Health Organization are telling us that they have the situation under control." Save the Children's Graeme Kenna says authorities are now searching to see how many other people could be affected by leprosy.

